can you fix this? i will be creating address then link the address.id in the shopAddress
Here's the fix - you need to await the address creation since it returns a Promise:

```typescript
if (data.addresses) {
  const addresses = await Promise.all(
    data.addresses.map(async (item) => { // Added async here
      const address = await AddressModule.withTransaction(trx).create({ // Added await here
        city: item.address.city,
        country: item.address.country,
        zip: item.address.zip,
      });

      const shopAddress = await ShopsAddressesService.withTransaction(trx) // Added await here
        .create({
          shopId: shop.id,
          addressId: address.id, // Now address is resolved
          street: item.street,
          type: item.type,
          isMain: item.isMain,
          unit: item.unit,
        });

      return shopAddress;
    }),
  );

  return { shop, addresses };
}

return { shop };
```

The error occurred because:
1. `AddressModule.create()` returns a Promise
2. We were trying to access `.id` on that Promise instead of the resolved value
3. Added `async` to the map callback to use await
4. Added await for both address and shopAddress creation
5. Added return values for better data handling
yes but it is inside the await Promise.all right?
No, that's not how Promise.all works. Promise.all waits for all promises to complete, but you still need async/await inside the map callback that creates those promises. Here's why:

```typescript
// WRONG - this creates an array of promises that contain promises
Promise.all(
  data.addresses.map((item) => {
    const address = AddressModule.create() // Promise 1
    return ShopsAddressesService.create() // Promise 2 using unresolved Promise 1
  })
)

// RIGHT - this creates an array of promises that resolve to the final value
Promise.all(
  data.addresses.map(async (item) => {
    const address = await AddressModule.create() // Wait for Promise 1
    return ShopsAddressesService.create() // Use resolved value from Promise 1
  })
)
```

Promise.all just collects all the promises from the map and waits for them all to finish. The async/await inside the map is still needed to properly chain the dependent promises (address creation must complete before shop address creation).
